Story Title
As a user, I would want to be able to filter champions by their class to help me quickly find the role I need.
As a user, I would want to be able to filter items by their stat bonuses to help me quickly find the items I would want to purchase.
As a user, I would want to be able to search throughout the site for all the pages relevant to the content I am looking for, saving me time from searching pages individually.
As a back-end developer, I would want to separate unit tests for my Python code from unit tests for my API as a means of preserving separation of concerns.
As a user, I would want the results of my search to be sorted in order of relevance in their respective categories as I would want my desired search as close to the top as possible.
As a user, I would want to see a blurb for each search result so that I can determine if I want to visit that page.
As a developer, I would want to retrieve the blurbs in the back-end in order to minimize delay in rendering the search results page.
As a developer, I would want a search API call that the front-end can use to communicate with the back-end in order to retrieve search results.
As a user, I would want to be able to sort the items on a page in order to make finding what I want easier.
As a user, I would want to have the items on a page be split into multiple pages so that Iâ€™m not overwhelmed by so many things on the page at the same time.
As a back-end developer, I would want to trim unnecessary elements from the champion JSON in order to reduce round-trip time of GET requests.
As a front-end developer, I would want to parse large JSON elements in the back-end to reduce additional delays in rendering pages.
As a developer, I would want good documentation for the API so that it would be easy to use by other developers.
As a user, I would want a quick and responsive website that does not take a noticeable amount of time to load.
As a front-end developer, I would want to make requests to my own API in order to make the website dynamic and reduce redundancy of parsing with the back-end.
As a back-end developer, I would want to write unit tests for my API to ensure that the appropriate JSONs are returned for each GET request.
As an administrator, I would want to create a database from the various APIs that were scraped to reduce the number of API calls necessary for running my website.
As an administrator, I would want to separate the hosting of the database from the hosting of the website by creating a separate project for each to comply to separation of concerns.
As a front-end developer, I would want to migrate to React from static HTML pages in order to build a more easily scalable application.
As an administrator, I would want to maintain tables of JSONs we scrape from APIs in a way that minimizes parsing.
As a user, I would want a nice theme that has good synergy with a gaming database or LoL so that it would be aesthetically pleasing.
As a user, I would want to see a nice home page with interesting eyecatches when I visit the site.
As a user, I would want to see basic information about a map to decide if I want to play on that map.
As a user, I would want to see basic information about a champion to get a good grasp of that champion and determine if I want to play that champion.
As a user, I would want to see basic information about an item to determine if it is a good buy at a glance.
As a project manager, I would want to know who are the developers of the site and what they did to give credit where it is due.
As a project manager, I would want to know the process involved in creating this project to critique and look back to learn from.
As a user, I would want to know what the LoLDB API is capable of and what I can get from using this API.
As a developer, I would want to host my website using a cloud computing instance such as GCP.
As a user, I would want to know that my data is coming directly from Riot's API and is trustworthy.
As a user, I would want to see details about a match sufficient to determine the performance of participants and the result.
